challengeName: Master Data Management - Error Identification and Analysis
detailedRequirements:
Background

A few weeks ago, we ran a marathon match on master data management aimed at predicting which pairs of records contained a duplicate (“Marathon Match”).

The Marathon Match was successful, and we obtained 5 winning solutions (“Winning Algorithms”). The system test score and rank of the Winning Algorithms appears below.

Rank Contestant System Test Score
1 Psyho 558,958.03
2 nofto 534,448.61
3 wleite 534,270.41
4 nhzp339 520,368.74
5 CatalinT 482,995.36

 

The Winning Algorithms all used random forests or variants thereof to predict which pairs of records contained a duplicate, and, in general, follow the steps described below:

1. Parse the data set containing potential pairs of duplicate records. 

2. Identify pairs of candidate duplicate records

3. Create features for a predictive model

4. Predict the probability that each pair of candidate records contains a duplicate

Steps 2 and 3 are likely to contain the most important ways in which the Winning Algorithms differ meaningfully.

Marathon Match Data Description and Duplicate Record Creation

To create the data set for the Marathon Match (“Contest Data Set”), we started with the Original Dataset, duplicated a subset of records, and changed the field values of one of the members of the pair of duplicate records.

The Contest Data Set is in csv format with the following columns:

  1. ID (Integer) - Index from 0 to n-1

  2. Name (String) - Provider name

  3. Address (String) - Provider address

  4. Taxonomies (String) - Comma separated list of healthcare taxonomies

Nb. Multiple provider taxonomies may be given for a single provider.

Ground truth for the training set is provided in a .csv file as a list of duplicate pairs. Each row corresponds to the two comma separated id numbers being a duplicate pair.

Types of Errors

We have identified 4 different changes that could be made to any single 1 of the Name, Address, and Taxonomies fields in the Contest Data Set.

Deletion = abc -> ac

Addition = abc -> aabc

Transposition = abc -> bac

Case Change = A -> a or a -> A

Note that substitution = abc -> adc = Deletion (abc -> ac) + Addition (ac -> adc).

There may be more changes that could be introduced into a single field of the Contest Data Set. Furthermore, changes involving multiple fields are possible.

Define the set of possible changes to create a Contest Data Set as “Types of Errors”

Objectives

- Identify as many Types of Errors as possible that could appear in the Contest Data Set.

- Write code that creates a new Contest Data Set containing the Types of Errors of your choosing (“Revised Contest Data Set”).

- Change the ranks of the Winning Algorithms as much as possible when they are run against your Revised Contest Data Set.

Contest Materials

The data and code from the Marathon Match can be found here:  https://drive.google.com/file/d/0ByjxTGykXQjAUWNWLXFaNmVGRWs/view?usp=sharing

To complete these objectives, please use the following from the previous contest:

  1. Contest statement

  2. Original Data Set

  3. Description of the Types of Errors in the Contest Data Set

  4. Python code used to create the Contest Data Set and ground truth

  5. Contest Data Set

  6. Contest ground truth

  7. Winning Algorithm

     a. Code
     b. Saved model
     c. Report

Suggested Approach

We suggest you proceed as follows.

  1. Review the Original Data Set.

  2. Read the Description of the Types of Errors in the Contest Data Set.

  3. Brainstorm all the possible Types of Errors that could appear your Revised Contest Data Set.

  4. Write code to create:

    a. Your Revised Contest Data Set, containing duplicate records with the Types of Errors of your choosing; and
    b. The ground truth for your Revised Contest Data Set.
     

  5. On your machine, run the Winning Algorithms against your Revised Contest Data Set and the corresponding ground truth.

  6. Score the Winning Algorithms with the Brier Score in the contest statement, not the Score.

  7. Note the change in the ranks of the Winning Algorithms.

  8. Alter your Revised Contest Data Set and the corresponding ground truth to change the ranks of the Winning Algorithms as much as possible.

Please let us know if you have trouble running the Winning Algorithms on your machine.

Scoring

Being an ideation contest, the scoring of submissions will be subjective based on client review.  The the criteria for evaluating the submissions are:

- The number of unique Types of Errors they contain; and

- The degree to which they alter the ranking of the Winning Algorithms when the same are run against the Revised Contest Data Set and the corresponding ground truth.

Please feel free to ask more specific questions in the forum, and if appropriate, we will answer them.

Report

Your report must be at least 2 pages long, contain the Approach information described below:

Approach Used

Please describe your approach so that we know what you did even before seeing the code to create your Revised Contest Data Set and the corresponding ground truth. This section must contain at least the following:

  • - Descriptions and examples of the Types of Errors you introduced in your Revised Contest Data Set

  • - Statistics describing your Revised Contest Data Set

    • Total records

    • Total total duplicate records (i.e., the total number of 1s in the ground truth)

    • Frequency of each Type of Errors among the total duplicate records

  • - Justification for Types of Errors used and the frequencies with which they occur

  • - References to specific lines of your code that introduce each Type of Error

  • - Potential improvements to your approach

  1. A single csv file containing a Revised Contest Data Set (defined below).

  1. A complete report at least 2 pages long outlining how you created your Revised Contest Data Set and the Types of Errors (defined below) it contains. The required content appears in the “Report” section below.
